[4] Cholera - Mozambique (Central Provinces)
Date: Wed, 8 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique (Maputo) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200602080121.html>

At least 3 people have died of cholera, out of a total number of 1506
cases diagnosed in 3 central Mozambican provinces -- Sofala, Manica,
and Zambezia -- since the start of 2006, reports an issue of the
Maputo daily "Noticias".
Sofala, where the 3 deaths were reported, is the worst-affected
province, with 1327 cases notified. In Beira, the provincial
capital, 533 cases were diagnosed, followed by the district of Caia,
on the south bank of the Zambezi, and the town of Dondo, about 30
kilometers from Beira, with 426 and 291 cases respectively. Other
affected areas in Sofala are the districts of Nhamatanda, where 53
cases were notified, and Marromeu, with 24 cases.
To illustrate the seriousness of the situation in Sofala, the health
authorities told reporters on Wed, 8 Feb 2006, that in the previous
24 hours Beira had notified 18 new cases while another 18 were
diagnosed in Dondo.
In Zambezia, 128 cases have been reported, 75 of them in Gile
district, 24 in the provincial capital, Quelimane, 15 in Namacurra,
and 14 in the Mopeia. As for Manica, so far 51 cases have been
detected, the vast majority of them (49) in the provincial capital,
Chimoio.
The health authorities say that the epidemic has been stable in
Manica and Zambezia, with an average of 1 to 2 cases a day, but a
cholera alert remains in place. It is feared that the disease could
spread to other provinces: heavy rains, and poor sanitation and
drainage provide ideal conditions for the spread of a water-borne
disease such as cholera. Prevention education campaigns against this
epidemic are being carried out across the country.
