[7] Shigellosis - Yemen (Al-Jawf Province)
Date: Mon, 6 Feb 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Alertnet Reuters News & IRIN News [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/e65acc3f31ba8f3588e5fa6829f9bdc5.htm>

Health teams in eastern Yemen continued work on Mon, 6 Feb 2006, to
halt the spread of dysentery, from which several children have
already died, according to local health officials. The prime symptom
of dysentery is diarrhea containing blood. The illness can be fatal
when caused by the shigella bacterium, which has been found in recent
cases.
"More than 400 children have been treated since Saturday, 4 Feb 2006,
in the Khub wa Shath district, where 6 teams from the Ministry of
Health have been working to combat the disease," said Ali Naji Abu
Hadra, a health official supervising field teams in al-Jawf province,
167 km east of the capital, Sana.
"There were 11 confirmed cases of death among children in the
district of Khub wa Shath up until Mon, 6 Feb 2006, as a result of
the disease," he added.
Abu Hadra declined, however, to say how many children are already
infected, but confirmed that medical teams would carry on working in
the affected area.
"We can't estimate how many children are infected in the whole
district, but teams will continue until the disease is eradicated,"
Abu Hadra said. According to the health ministry, the disease first
broke out in al-Jawf province on 2 Feb 2006.
